
@startuml

' Define classes with attributes and relationships

class Provider {
    +String name
    +String location
}

class Cruise {
    +int cruiseNumber
    +String cruiseName
    +Date startDate
    +Date endDate
}

class Employee {
    +String name
    +String socialSecurityNumber
}

class Guest {
    +String name
    +boolean isVIP
}

class Ship {
    +String name
    +int numberOfDecks
    +double length
    +int passengerCapacity
}

class TravelAgency {
    +String name
    +String address
}

class Booking {
    +String bookingNumber
    +Date bookingDate
}

class DestinationArea {
    +String name
    +String seaName
}

class Show {
    +String title
    +int duration
}

class Ticket {
    +int ticketId
}

' Relationships

Provider "1" -- "0..*" Cruise : organizes
Cruise "1" -- "1..*" Employee : requires
Cruise "1" -- "1..*" Guest : includes
Cruise "1" -- "1" Ship : uses
Cruise "1" -- "1" DestinationArea : heads to
Cruise "1" -- "1" TravelAgency : booked through
TravelAgency "1" -- "0..*" Booking : makes
Booking "1" -- "1" Cruise : for
Cruise "1" -- "0..*" Show : offers
Cruise "1" -- "1..*" Ticket : issues
Guest "1" -- "0..*" Ticket : has (1 per cruise)
Ticket "1" -- "1" Cruise : belongs to

@enduml

---

### Notes:
- All multiplicity constraints are defined according to the system requirements.
- The `Ticket` class ensures that a guest can have multiple tickets but only one per cruise.
- The `Employee`, `Guest`, and `Show` are associated with a cruise as required.
- Each class includes relevant attributes based on the description.

